"Manzello D.P., Brandt M., Smith T.B., Lirman D., Hendee J.C., Nemeth R.S.","Hurricanes benefit bleached corals",2007,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","104","29",,"12035","12039",,,10.1073/pnas.0701194104,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34547507622&partnerID=40&md5=ac0711e599951a9b1e0f64b83d8c2d5c","Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, 4301 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Rosenstiel School of Marine and Atmospheric Science, University of Miami, 4600 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Center for Marine and Environmental Studies, University of the Virgin Islands, 2 John Brewer's Bay, St. Thomas, 00802, Virgin Islands (U.S.)","Manzello, D.P., Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, 4301 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States, Rosenstiel School of Marine and Atmospheric Science, University of Miami, 4600 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Brandt, M., Rosenstiel School of Marine and Atmospheric Science, University of Miami, 4600 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Smith, T.B., Center for Marine and Environmental Studies, University of the Virgin Islands, 2 John Brewer's Bay, St. Thomas, 00802, Virgin Islands (U.S.); Lirman, D., Rosenstiel School of Marine and Atmospheric Science, University of Miami, 4600 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Hendee, J.C., Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, 4301 Rickenbacker Causeway, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Nemeth, R.S., Center for Marine and Environmental Studies, University of the Virgin Islands, 2 John Brewer's Bay, St. Thomas, 00802, Virgin Islands (U.S.)","Recent, global mass-mortalities of reef corals due to record warm sea temperatures have led researchers to consider global warming as one of the most significant threats to the persistence of coral reef ecosystems. The passage of a hurricane can alleviate thermal stress on coral reefs, highlighting the potential for hurricane-associated cooling to mitigate climate change impacts. We provide evidence that hurricane-induced cooling was responsible for the documented differences in the extent and recovery time of coral bleaching between the Florida Reef Tract and the U.S. Virgin Islands during the Caribbean-wide 2005 bleaching event. These results are the only known scenario where the effects of a hurricane can benefit a stressed marine community. © 2007 by The National Academy of Sciences of the USA.","Coral bleaching; Hurricane cooling; Thermal stress","article; climate change; cooling; coral; coral reef; endosymbiont; endosymbiosis; environmental stress; environmental temperature; greenhouse effect; hurricane; nonhuman; priority journal; temperature stress; United States; Animals; Anthozoa; Cold; Data Collection; Florida; Heating; Natural Disasters; Oceans and Seas; Regression Analysis; Time Factors; Anthozoa",,,,,,"Glynn, P.W., (1993) Coral Reefs, 12, pp. 1-17; Brown, B.E., (1997) Coral Reefs, 16 S, pp. 129-138; Berkelmans, R., (2002) Mar Ecol Prog Ser, 229, pp. 73-82; Hoegh-Guldberg, O., (1999) Mar Freshwat Res, 50, pp. 839-866; Hughes, T.P., Baird, A.H., Bellwood, D.R., Card, M., Connolly, S.R., Folke, C., Grosberg, R., Kleypas, J., (2003) Science, 301, pp. 929-933; Gray, W.M., (1979) Meteorology Over the Tropical Oceans, pp. 155-218. , ed Shaw DB R Meteorol Soc, Berkshire, UK, pp; Cornillon, P., Stramma, L., Price, J.F., (1987) Nature, 326, pp. 373-375; Price, J.F., Sanford, T.B., Forristall, G.Z., (1994) J Phys Oceanogr, 24, pp. 233-260; Xie, L., Pietrafesa, U., Bohm, E., Zhang, C., Li, X., (1998) Geophys Res Lett, 25, pp. 769-772; Harmelin-Vivien, M.L., (1994) J Coast Res Spec Issue, 12, pp. 211-231; Lirman, D., Fong, P., (1997) Proc 8th Int Coral Reef S